---
import Page from '../../layouts/Page.astro';
---
<Page
  title="Kitchen Gadgets"
  description="Production-grade AI agent skills for every phase of software development. Browse, filter, and install engineering skills for Claude, Gemini, and any AI coding agent."
>

  <section class="page-hero container">
    <h1><span class="h1-emoji">🔧</span> Kitchen Gadgets</h1>
    <p>Production-grade AI agent skills for every phase of software development. Click any gadget to see how it works and grab the install snippet for your project.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta">
      <span>23 skills · 6 phases</span>
      <a href="https://github.com/addyosmani/agent-skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="source-link">
        ⭐ View source on GitHub
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container gadgets-wrap">

    <!-- Phase flow bar -->
    <div class="phase-flow" id="phase-flow" role="tablist" aria-label="Filter by phase"></div>

    <!-- Filter tabs -->
    <div class="filter-tabs" id="filter-tabs">
      <button class="filter-tab active" data-filter="all">All</button>
      <button class="filter-tab" data-filter="Define">🎯 Define</button>
      <button class="filter-tab" data-filter="Plan">📋 Plan</button>
      <button class="filter-tab" data-filter="Build">💻 Build</button>
      <button class="filter-tab" data-filter="Review">🔍 Review</button>
      <button class="filter-tab" data-filter="Ship">🚀 Ship</button>
      <button class="filter-tab" data-filter="Maintain">🛡️ Maintain</button>
    </div>

    <p class="gadgets-count"><strong id="visible-count">23</strong> gadgets · Source: <a href="https://github.com/addyosmani/agent-skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener">addyosmani/agent-skills</a> · Works with Claude, Gemini, any AI coding agent</p>

    <!-- Grid -->
    <div class="gadgets-grid" id="gadgets-grid"></div>

    <!-- Detail panel -->
    <div class="gadget-detail" id="gadget-detail"></div>

    <!-- Tip -->
    <div class="callout">
      <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
      <div>
        <strong>How to use these gadgets</strong>
        <p>Copy the install snippet and paste it into a message to your AI agent — or add the raw GitHub URL to your <code>CLAUDE.md</code> / <code>AGENTS.md</code> file so it's always available. Each skill encodes a repeatable engineering workflow.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

</Page>

<style>
.page-hero {
  padding: var(--s12) 0 var(--s6);
  max-width: var(--container-narrow);
}
.page-hero h1 {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem);
  margin: 0 0 var(--s3);
}
.page-hero p { color: var(--text-2); font-size: 1.05rem; margin: 0 0 var(--s3); }
.hero-meta {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--s4);
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  color: var(--text-3);
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}
.source-link {
  color: var(--accent);
  text-decoration: none;
  font-weight: 600;
}
.source-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

.gadgets-wrap { padding-bottom: var(--s20); }

/* Phase flow */
.phase-flow {
  display: flex;
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: var(--r3);
  overflow: hidden;
  margin-bottom: var(--s5);
}
.phase-pill {
  flex: 1;
  padding: var(--s3) var(--s2);
  text-align: center;
  background: var(--surface);
  border: none;
  border-right: 1px solid var(--border);
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: background var(--t-fast);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
}
.phase-pill:last-child { border-right: none; }
.phase-pill:hover { background: var(--bg-alt); }
.phase-pill.active { background: var(--accent); color: #fff; }
.phase-pill-icon { font-size: 1rem; display: block; }
.phase-pill-label { font-size: 0.65rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .05em; display: block; margin-top: 2px; }
.phase-pill-count { font-size: 0.6rem; opacity: .7; display: block; }

/* Filter tabs */
.filter-tabs { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: var(--s2); margin-bottom: var(--s4); }
.filter-tab {
  padding: 4px var(--s3);
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: 999px;
  background: var(--surface);
  font-size: 0.82rem;
  font-weight: 500;
  color: var(--text-2);
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: all var(--t-fast);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
}
.filter-tab:hover { border-color: var(--accent); color: var(--text); }
.filter-tab.active { background: var(--accent); border-color: var(--accent); color: #fff; font-weight: 700; }

.gadgets-count { font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--text-3); margin: 0 0 var(--s5); }
.gadgets-count a { color: inherit; }

/* Gadget grid */
.gadgets-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr));
  gap: var(--s3);
  margin-bottom: var(--s5);
}
.gadget-card {
  padding: var(--s4);
  border: 2px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: var(--r3);
  background: var(--surface);
  cursor: pointer;
  text-align: left;
  width: 100%;
  transition: border-color var(--t-fast), transform var(--t-fast), box-shadow var(--t-fast);
  position: relative;
  font-family: var(--font-body);
}
.gadget-card:hover { border-color: var(--accent); transform: translateY(-2px); box-shadow: var(--shadow-md); }
.gadget-card.active { border-color: var(--accent); background: var(--accent-light); }

.gc-icon { font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: var(--s2); display: block; }
.gc-cat {
  display: inline-block;
  font-size: 0.62rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .06em;
  padding: 2px 7px; border-radius: 999px;
  background: var(--accent-light); border: 1px solid var(--accent-border); color: var(--accent);
  margin-bottom: var(--s2);
}
.gc-name { font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text); display: block; margin-bottom: 3px; line-height: 1.3; }
.gc-tagline { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.4; }
.gc-indicator {
  position: absolute; top: var(--s3); right: var(--s3);
  width: 18px; height: 18px; background: var(--accent); border-radius: 50%;
  display: none; align-items: center; justify-content: center; color: #fff; font-size: 0.6rem;
}
.gadget-card.active .gc-indicator { display: flex; }

/* Detail panel */
.gadget-detail { display: none; margin-bottom: var(--s6); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); background: var(--bg-alt); overflow: hidden; }
.gadget-detail.open { display: block; animation: fadeUp .2s ease; }
@keyframes fadeUp { from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(8px); } to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); } }

.detail-header { padding: var(--s5) var(--s6); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--surface); display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: var(--s4); flex-wrap: wrap; }
.detail-icon { font-size: 2.5rem; flex-shrink: 0; }
.detail-header-text { flex: 1; min-width: 200px; }
.detail-name { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 0 0 4px; color: var(--text); }
.detail-tagline { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 var(--s3); }
.detail-close { margin-left: auto; flex-shrink: 0; align-self: flex-start; }

.detail-body { padding: var(--s5) var(--s6); }
.detail-section { margin-bottom: var(--s5); }
.detail-section-title {
  font-size: 0.68rem; font-weight: 800; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .08em;
  color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: var(--s3);
  display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--s2);
}
.detail-section-title::after { content: ''; flex: 1; height: 1px; background: var(--border); }
.detail-overview { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.7; margin: 0; }

.detail-when { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s2); }
.detail-when li { display: flex; gap: var(--s2); font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.5; }
.detail-when li::before { content: '✓'; color: var(--accent); font-weight: 700; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 1px; }

.principles-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: var(--s3); }
.principle { padding: var(--s3) var(--s4); background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r2); }
.principle-title { font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 3px; }
.principle-desc { font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.4; }

.install-box { background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r2); padding: var(--s4); }
.install-label { font-size: 0.68rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .06em; color: var(--text-3); margin-bottom: var(--s2); }
.install-snippet { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--text); background: var(--bg-alt); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r1); padding: var(--s3) var(--s4); white-space: pre-wrap; word-break: break-all; margin-bottom: var(--s3); line-height: 1.6; }
.install-actions { display: flex; gap: var(--s2); align-items: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
.copy-confirm { font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--green); font-weight: 600; display: none; }

/* Callout */
.callout { display: flex; gap: var(--s4); padding: var(--s5); background: var(--accent-light); border: 1px solid var(--accent-border); border-radius: var(--r3); }
.callout-icon { font-size: 1.5rem; flex-shrink: 0; }
.callout strong { display: block; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: var(--s2); color: var(--text); }
.callout p { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-2); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
.callout code { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8em; background: var(--bg-alt); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 3px; }

/* Btn */
.btn { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--s2); padding: var(--s2) var(--s4); border-radius: var(--r2); font-size: 0.82rem; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; border: 1px solid transparent; transition: all var(--t-fast); font-family: var(--font-body); text-decoration: none; }
.btn-primary { background: var(--accent); color: #fff; border-color: var(--accent); }
.btn-primary:hover { background: var(--accent-hover); }
.btn-secondary { background: transparent; color: var(--text-2); border-color: var(--border); }
.btn-secondary:hover { background: var(--bg-alt); color: var(--text); }
.btn-sm { padding: 3px var(--s3); font-size: 0.78rem; }

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .phase-flow { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); }
  .gadgets-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  .detail-header { padding: var(--s4); }
  .detail-body { padding: var(--s4); }
}
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  .gadgets-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
}
</style>

<script>
const BASE_RAW = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/addyosmani/agent-skills/main/skills/';
const BASE_GH  = 'https://github.com/addyosmani/agent-skills/tree/main/skills/';

const PHASES = [
  { id: 'Define',   icon: '🎯', label: 'Define',   desc: 'Clarify intent before building' },
  { id: 'Plan',     icon: '📋', label: 'Plan',     desc: 'Organise the work' },
  { id: 'Build',    icon: '💻', label: 'Build',    desc: 'Active development' },
  { id: 'Review',   icon: '🔍', label: 'Review',   desc: 'Quality gates' },
  { id: 'Ship',     icon: '🚀', label: 'Ship',     desc: 'Deploy safely' },
  { id: 'Maintain', icon: '🛡️', label: 'Maintain', desc: 'Ongoing care' },
];

const GADGETS = [
  // Define
  { id:'interview-me', icon:'🎤', cat:'Define', name:'Interview Me', tagline:'Close the gap between what you ask for and what you actually want', overview:'What people ask for and what they actually want are different things. This skill extracts real intent through one-question-at-a-time dialogue — before any plan, spec, or code exists.', when:['The ask is missing who, why, what success looks like, or the constraint','Someone says "build me X" without "for whom" or "why now"','You\'re about to silently fill in ambiguous requirements','Triggered by: "interview me", "grill me", "stress-test my thinking"'], principles:[{t:'One question at a time',d:'Never ask two questions at once — one focused question per turn.'},{t:'Attach your best guess',d:'Always include your current interpretation so the user can correct or confirm it.'},{t:'Before everything else',d:'This runs before idea-refine, spec, or any planning.'}] },
  { id:'idea-refine', icon:'💡', cat:'Define', name:'Idea Refine', tagline:'Turn raw concepts into sharp, actionable ideas worth building', overview:'Refines raw ideas through structured divergent and convergent thinking. First expands possibilities, then evaluates and converges, then produces a concrete one-pager moving work forward.', when:['An idea is still vague or underspecified','You need to stress-test assumptions before committing to a plan','You want to expand options before converging on one','Triggered by: "ideate", "refine this idea", "stress-test my plan"'], principles:[{t:'Diverge first',d:'Generate variations and alternatives before evaluating.'},{t:'Stress-test',d:'Surface hidden assumptions and cluster related ideas.'},{t:'Converge to a one-pager',d:'Produce a concrete brief that moves work forward.'}] },
  { id:'spec-driven-development', icon:'📐', cat:'Define', name:'Spec-Driven Development', tagline:'Write the specification before writing any code', overview:'Write a structured specification before writing any code. The spec is the shared source of truth — it defines what we\'re building, why, and how we\'ll know it\'s done. Code without a spec is guessing.', when:['Starting a new project or feature with unclear requirements','Requirements are ambiguous or exist only as a vague idea','The change touches multiple files or modules','The task would take more than 30 minutes to implement'], principles:[{t:'Define success criteria',d:'Specs must include measurable acceptance criteria, not just descriptions.'},{t:'Document trade-offs',d:'Record what was considered and rejected, not just what was chosen.'},{t:'Align before building',d:'The spec is a contract. Get agreement before writing code.'}] },
  // Plan
  { id:'planning-and-task-breakdown', icon:'📋', cat:'Plan', name:'Planning & Task Breakdown', tagline:'Decompose any feature into small, verifiable tasks', overview:'Decompose work into small, verifiable tasks with explicit acceptance criteria. Every task should be small enough to implement, test, and verify in a single focused session.', when:['You have a spec and need to break it into implementable units','A task feels too large or vague to start','Work needs to be parallelised across multiple agents or sessions','The implementation order isn\'t obvious'], principles:[{t:'Thin vertical slices',d:'Each task delivers working, testable behaviour — not just a layer.'},{t:'Explicit acceptance criteria',d:'Every task has a verifiable definition of done.'},{t:'Ordered dependencies',d:'Map what must exist before each task can begin.'}] },
  { id:'incremental-implementation', icon:'🪜', cat:'Plan', name:'Incremental Implementation', tagline:'Build one piece, test it, verify it, then expand', overview:'Build in thin vertical slices. Avoid implementing an entire feature in one pass. Each increment should leave the system in a working, testable state.', when:['Implementing any multi-file change','Building a new feature from a task breakdown','Refactoring existing code','Any time you\'re tempted to write more than ~100 lines before testing'], principles:[{t:'Always working state',d:'Each commit leaves the system deployable — no "half done" states.'},{t:'Test before expanding',d:'Verify each slice before building on top of it.'},{t:'Small batches',d:'Smaller changes are easier to review, debug, and roll back.'}] },
  { id:'context-engineering', icon:'🧠', cat:'Plan', name:'Context Engineering', tagline:'Feed your agent the right information at the right time', overview:'Context is the single biggest lever for agent output quality — too little and the agent hallucinates, too much and it loses focus. Context engineering is the practice of deliberately curating what the agent sees, when, and how.', when:['Starting a new coding session','Agent output quality is declining (wrong patterns, hallucinated APIs)','Switching between different parts of a codebase','The agent is not following project conventions'], principles:[{t:'Hierarchy matters',d:'Project rules beat session instructions beat defaults.'},{t:'Just-in-time loading',d:'Load relevant context when it\'s needed, not all at once.'},{t:'Rules files',d:'CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md encode permanent project context so you don\'t repeat yourself.'}] },
  { id:'using-agent-skills', icon:'🗺️', cat:'Plan', name:'Using Agent Skills', tagline:'Discover and invoke the right skill for any task', overview:'The meta-skill that governs how all other skills are discovered and invoked. Maps tasks to development phases and selects the appropriate skill. Use when starting a session or when unsure which skill applies.', when:['Starting a new session and unsure which skill to apply','A task doesn\'t obviously map to a known workflow','Onboarding to agent-assisted development for the first time'], principles:[{t:'Phase-first thinking',d:'Identify the development phase before selecting a skill.'},{t:'Skills are processes',d:'Each skill encodes a workflow, not just a capability.'},{t:'Composable',d:'Skills chain: interview-me → spec → plan → build → review → ship.'}] },
  // Build
  { id:'api-and-interface-design', icon:'🔌', cat:'Build', name:'API & Interface Design', tagline:'Design stable interfaces that are hard to misuse', overview:'Design stable, well-documented interfaces that make the right thing easy and the wrong thing hard. Applies to REST APIs, GraphQL, module boundaries, component props, and any surface where code talks to other code.', when:['Designing new API endpoints or GraphQL schemas','Defining module boundaries or contracts between teams','Creating component prop interfaces','Changing existing public interfaces'], principles:[{t:'Hard to misuse',d:'The right path should be obvious; wrong paths should fail loudly.'},{t:'Stable contracts',d:'Public interfaces are a promise. Design for longevity.'},{t:'Document intent',d:'Interfaces should express what they do, not how they do it.'}] },
  { id:'frontend-ui-engineering', icon:'🎨', cat:'Build', name:'Frontend UI Engineering', tagline:'Build production-quality UIs that look designed, not generated', overview:'Build production-quality interfaces that are accessible, performant, and visually polished. The goal is UI that looks like it was built by a design-aware engineer — not generated by an AI.', when:['Building new UI components or pages','Modifying existing user-facing interfaces','Implementing responsive layouts','Adding interactivity or state management'], principles:[{t:'Accessibility first',d:'Semantic HTML, ARIA, keyboard nav — not an afterthought.'},{t:'Design system adherence',d:'Use existing tokens and components. Don\'t invent new patterns.'},{t:'No AI aesthetic',d:'Generic gradients and misaligned spacing are red flags.'}] },
  { id:'test-driven-development', icon:'🧪', cat:'Build', name:'Test-Driven Development', tagline:'Write the failing test before writing the code', overview:'Write a failing test before writing the code that makes it pass. For bug fixes, reproduce the bug with a test first. Tests are proof — "seems right" is not done.', when:['Implementing any new logic or behaviour','Fixing any bug (the Prove-It Pattern)','Modifying existing functionality','Any change that could break existing behaviour'], principles:[{t:'Red → Green → Refactor',d:'Write failing test, make it pass, clean it up. Never skip steps.'},{t:'The Prove-It Pattern',d:'Reproduce the bug with a test first — it proves the fix when it goes green.'},{t:'Tests are documentation',d:'Good tests describe behaviour, not implementation details.'}] },
  { id:'source-driven-development', icon:'📚', cat:'Build', name:'Source-Driven Development', tagline:'Ground every implementation decision in official documentation', overview:'Every framework-specific code decision must be backed by official documentation. Training data goes stale, APIs get deprecated. This skill ensures code that traces back to authoritative sources.', when:['Building with any framework where correctness matters','Writing boilerplate or patterns that will be copied across a project','Any time you\'re about to write framework-specific code from memory'], principles:[{t:'Cite your sources',d:'Every framework pattern should link back to official docs.'},{t:'Training data is stale',d:'APIs deprecate. Always verify against the current version docs.'},{t:'Show your work',d:'Let the user verify the source — builds trust and catches errors.'}] },
  { id:'doubt-driven-development', icon:'🤔', cat:'Build', name:'Doubt-Driven Development', tagline:'Adversarial review of non-trivial decisions before they stand', overview:'A confident answer is not a correct one. Long sessions accumulate context that quietly turns assumptions into "facts." This skill materialises a fresh-context reviewer — biased to disprove, not approve.', when:['A decision introduces or modifies branching logic','The change crosses a module or service boundary','Stakes are high (production, security-sensitive, irreversible)','Correctness matters more than speed'], principles:[{t:'Fresh context',d:'The reviewer hasn\'t accumulated the session\'s assumptions.'},{t:'In-flight, not post-hoc',d:'Verify while course-correction is cheap, not after committing.'},{t:'Non-trivial threshold',d:'Only decisions that could silently break behaviour need this check.'}] },
  // Review
  { id:'code-review-and-quality', icon:'🔍', cat:'Review', name:'Code Review & Quality', tagline:'Multi-axis review before any change merges', overview:'Multi-dimensional code review covering five axes: correctness, readability, architecture, security, and performance. Every change gets reviewed before merge — no exceptions, including agent-generated code.', when:['Before merging any PR or change','After completing a feature implementation','When another agent produced code you need to evaluate','After any bug fix (review both the fix and the regression test)'], principles:[{t:'Five axes',d:'Correctness, readability, architecture, security, performance — all matter.'},{t:'Improve, don\'t perfect',d:'Approve if it improves overall health. Don\'t block for style preferences.'},{t:'No exceptions',d:'Every change gets reviewed — agent-generated code included.'}] },
  { id:'code-simplification', icon:'✂️', cat:'Review', name:'Code Simplification', tagline:'Reduce complexity while preserving exact behaviour', overview:'Simplify code by reducing complexity while preserving exact behaviour. The goal is not fewer lines — it\'s code that is easier to read, understand, modify, and debug.', when:['After a feature is working but the implementation feels heavier than needed','During code review when readability or complexity issues are flagged','When you encounter deeply nested logic, long functions, or unclear names'], principles:[{t:'Behaviour preservation',d:'Simplification that changes behaviour is a bug, not an improvement.'},{t:'The new-teammate test',d:'Would someone new understand this faster? That\'s the benchmark.'},{t:'Delete > abstract',d:'Deleting code is almost always better than abstracting it.'}] },
  { id:'debugging-and-error-recovery', icon:'🐛', cat:'Review', name:'Debugging & Error Recovery', tagline:'Systematic root-cause analysis — no guessing', overview:'When something breaks, stop adding features, preserve evidence, and follow a structured process to find and fix the root cause. Guessing wastes time.', when:['Tests fail after a code change','The build breaks','Runtime behaviour doesn\'t match expectations','Something worked before and stopped working'], principles:[{t:'Preserve evidence',d:'Don\'t change anything before understanding the failure.'},{t:'Structured triage',d:'Follow the checklist — it surfaces root causes that guessing misses.'},{t:'Reproduce before fixing',d:'If you can\'t reproduce it, you don\'t understand it.'}] },
  { id:'browser-testing-with-devtools', icon:'🔬', cat:'Review', name:'Browser DevTools Testing', tagline:'Live browser inspection via Chrome DevTools MCP', overview:'Use Chrome DevTools MCP to give your agent eyes into the browser. Bridges the gap between static code analysis and live execution — the agent can see what the user sees.', when:['Building or modifying anything that renders in a browser','Debugging UI issues (layout, styling, interaction)','Analysing network requests and API responses','Verifying that a fix actually works in the browser'], principles:[{t:'Verify, don\'t guess',d:'See what the browser actually renders instead of inferring from code.'},{t:'Runtime data',d:'Console logs, network payloads, and DOM state tell you what static analysis can\'t.'},{t:'Requires DevTools MCP',d:'Needs the chrome-devtools MCP server configured in your agent.'}] },
  // Ship
  { id:'ci-cd-and-automation', icon:'⚙️', cat:'Ship', name:'CI/CD & Automation', tagline:'Automate quality gates so nothing bad reaches production', overview:'Automate quality gates so no change reaches production without passing tests, lint, type checking, and build. CI/CD is the enforcement mechanism for every other skill.', when:['Setting up a new project\'s CI pipeline','Adding or modifying automated checks','Configuring deployment pipelines'], principles:[{t:'Shift left',d:'A bug caught in linting costs minutes; caught in production costs hours.'},{t:'Faster is safer',d:'Smaller batches and more frequent releases reduce risk.'},{t:'No exceptions',d:'CI runs on every change. No bypassing, no "just this once."'}] },
  { id:'git-workflow-and-versioning', icon:'🌿', cat:'Ship', name:'Git Workflow & Versioning', tagline:'Treat commits as save points, history as documentation', overview:'Git is your safety net. Treat commits as save points, branches as sandboxes, and history as documentation. With AI agents generating code at high speed, disciplined version control is essential.', when:['Always — every code change flows through git','Making any commit, branch, or merge decision','Resolving conflicts'], principles:[{t:'Trunk-based dev',d:'Keep main always deployable. Short-lived branches merging within 1–3 days.'},{t:'Atomic commits',d:'Each commit is a single logical change with a clear message explaining why.'},{t:'Reversibility',d:'If you can\'t roll it back in 5 minutes, your deployment strategy needs work.'}] },
  { id:'shipping-and-launch', icon:'🚀', cat:'Ship', name:'Shipping & Launch', tagline:'Deploy safely with monitoring in place and a rollback plan ready', overview:'The goal is not just to deploy — it\'s to deploy safely, with monitoring in place, a rollback plan ready, and a clear understanding of what success looks like.', when:['Deploying a feature to production for the first time','Releasing a significant change to users','Migrating data or infrastructure','Any deployment that carries risk (all of them)'], principles:[{t:'Reversible by default',d:'If you can\'t roll back, you\'re not ready to ship.'},{t:'Observable',d:'Monitoring and alerting must be in place before the deploy button is pressed.'},{t:'Incremental',d:'Feature flags, canary releases, staged rollouts — never big-bang deploys.'}] },
